54A] hover:text-[#B8654A]/80 hover:underline font-sans font-medium\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"(Subscribe on Substack)\\\"}]]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-xs text-card-foreground/60 font-sans\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Hypnotherapist \\u0026 Peak Performance Coach\\\"}]]}]]}]]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"mb-12 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-border relative aspect-[16/9] w-full shadow-sm\\\",\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"img\\\",null,{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/blog/why-partner-triggers-you.jpg\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Why Your Partner Triggers You More Than Anyone Else on Earth\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"object-cover w-full h-full\\\"}]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose-custom\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Your boss can criticise you and you'll shrug it off by lunch. Your friend can cancel plans three times and you'll barely register it. But your partner gives you a look — one look — and your entire world destabilises.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"2\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"You've probably wondered if something is wrong with you. If you're too sensitive. If you chose the wrong person. If everyone else's relationship is calmer than yours.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"4\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Nothing is wrong with you. And here's why.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"6\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"The Neuroscience of Primary Attachment Bonds\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"8\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Your romantic partner occupies a unique neurological position in your brain. They are your primary attachment figure — the person your nervous system has designated as your primary source of safety, comfort, and co-regulation. This designation activates the same neural circuitry that once connected you to your earliest caregiver.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"10\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Read that again. The same circuits.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"12\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Dr. Sue Johnson, the creator of Emotionally Focused Therapy (EFT), describes adult romantic love as an attachment bond. Not metaphorically. Literally. The same brain regions that light up when an infant reaches for their mother — the anterior cingulate cortex, the insula, the ventral tegmental area — fire when you reach for your partner. And the same regions that activate during infant separation distress activate when you feel disconnected from your partner.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"14\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"This is why a dismissive comment from your partner can ruin your week while the same comment from a colleague would barely register. \\u003cstrong class=\\\\\\\"text-foreground font-semibold\\\\\\\"\\u003eThe stakes are neurologically different.\\u003c/strong\\u003e Your brain has categorised your partner as essential to your survival. Not because you're codependent. Because that's literally how human attachment works.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"16\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"The Amygdala Doesn't Know the Difference\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"18\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Here's where it gets fascinating — and painful. Your amygdala, the brain's threat-detection system, processes relational cues from your partner with the same urgency it processes physical danger. A contemptuous eye-roll activates the same neural alarm system as a growling dog.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"20\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Neuroscientist Dr. Jaak Panksepp's research on the PANIC/GRIEF system — one of seven core emotional circuits in the mammalian brain — shows that social separation distress is processed through the same neural pathways as physical pain. The anterior cingulate cortex, which lights up when you burn your hand on a stove, also lights up when you feel rejected by your partner.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"22\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"This is not a design flaw. This is evolutionary architecture. For most of human history, separation from your primary bond meant death. Your brain is wired to treat relational disconnection as a survival-level threat because, for hundreds of thousands of years, it was.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"24\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Why The Little Things Feel So Big\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"26\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"This explains something every couple fights about: the disproportionate reaction.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"30\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\\\\\\"I just said I was tired. Why are you acting like I insulted you?\\\\\\\"\\u003cbr /\\u003e\\\\\\\"All I did was look at my phone. Why is that such a big deal?\\\\\\\"\\u003cbr /\\u003e\\\\\\\"I forgot to call. It's not the end of the world.\\\\\\\"\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"32\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"To the partner saying these things, the behaviour genuinely seems minor. And on the surface, it is. But to the receiving partner's attachment system, each of these moments carries a deeper question:\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"36\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003cem class=\\\\\\\"text-[#B8654A]\\\\\\\"\\u003eAre you there for me?\\u003c/em\\u003e\\u003cbr /\\u003e\\u003cem class=\\\\\\\"text-[#B8654A]\\\\\\\"\\u003eDo I matter to you?\\u003c/em\\u003e\\u003cbr /\\u003e\\u003cem class=\\\\\\\"text-[#B8654A]\\\\\\\"\\u003eCan I count on you?\\u003c/em\\u003e\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"38\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"These are not dramatic questions. They are the fundamental questions of every attachment bond, asked silently and constantly by your nervous system. And when the answer feels like \\\\\\\"no\\\\\\\" — even for a moment, even unintentionally — the alarm system fires.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"40\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"The Role of Implicit Memory\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"42\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"In my hypnotherapy work, I help clients understand that their triggers are rarely about the present moment. They're about implicit memory — the body's stored record of every relational experience you've ever had, encoded without conscious awareness.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"44\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"When your partner doesn't respond to your text for three hours, your conscious mind might think \\\\\\\"they're probably busy.\\\\\\\" But your implicit memory might be replaying every moment in childhood when you called out and nobody came. The feeling isn't about the text. It's about a neural pathway that was carved years ago, now reactivated by a stimulus that your subconscious maps onto the original wound.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"46\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Using NLP submodality work, I guide clients to examine the internal representation of their trigger. What does it look like? Sound like? Feel like in the body? And almost invariably, the internal representation matches a scene from much earlier in their life. The partner is just the latest actor on a very old stage.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"48\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"How to Work With This Instead of Against It\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"50\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003cstrong class=\\\\\\\"text-foreground font-semibold\\\\\\\"\\u003eStep 1: Stop Pathologising the Intensity.\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"52\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Your strong reactions to your partner are not evidence that you're broken, that they're wrong for you, or that your relationship is failing. They're evidence that your attachment system is online and activated. That's what it's supposed to do. The intensity is proportional to the importance of the bond.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"54\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003cstrong class=\\\\\\\"text-foreground font-semibold\\\\\\\"\\u003eStep 2: Name the Deeper Question.\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"56\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Underneath every trigger is an attachment question. Start asking yourself: \\\\\\\"What am I really afraid of right now?\\\\\\\" Usually it's a variation of: \\\\\\\"Are you going to leave? Do you see me? Am I enough?\\\\\\\"\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"58\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"When you can name it — to yourself or to your partner — you transform the conversation from surface-level content (\\\\\\\"You forgot to buy milk\\\\\\\") to attachment-level truth (\\\\\\\"I needed to feel like I was on your mind\\\\\\\").\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"60\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003cstrong class=\\\\\\\"text-foreground font-semibold\\\\\\\"\\u003eStep 3: Respond to the Attachment Need, Not the Behaviour.\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"62\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"This one is for the partner on the receiving end of the trigger. When your partner has a disproportionate reaction, resist the urge to argue about proportionality. Instead, try to hear the attachment message underneath.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"64\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\\\\\\"You're upset about the phone? This feels bigger than the phone. What's happening for you right now?\\\\\\\"\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"66\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"This requires regulation on your part. It requires the capacity to not take their activation personally. But when you can do it — even sometimes, even imperfectly — you are offering your partner's nervous system exactly what it needs: the experience of being seen, heard, and met in their distress.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"68\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003cstrong class=\\\\\\\"text-foreground font-semibold\\\\\\\"\\u003eStep 4: Create Rituals of Connection.\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"70\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Gottman's research shows that stable couples have daily rituals of connection that serve as ongoing reassurance to the attachment system. A kiss goodbye that lasts at least six seconds. A daily check-in about each other's inner world. A weekly date that is protected from cancellation.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"72\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"These rituals aren't romantic extras. They are neurological maintenance. They keep the attachment system in a state of felt security so that when the inevitable conflicts arise, both partners have a deeper reservoir of trust to draw from.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",\\\"74\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-2xl font-bold text-foreground font-serif mt-12 mb-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"The Bottom Line\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"76\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"Your partner triggers you because they matter. Because your brain has placed them at the centre of your attachment world. Because the same neural architecture that once helped you survive infancy is now trying to help you navigate the most important relationship of your adult life.\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"78\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"The question is not \\\\\\\"how do I stop being triggered?\\\\\\\" That's like asking \\\\\\\"how do I stop having a nervous system?\\\\\\\" The question is: \\\\\\\"how do I work with my triggers in a way that brings me closer to my partner instead of driving us apart?\\\\\\\"\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",\\\"80\\\",{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-card-foreground/90 font-sans leading-[1.85] mb-6 text-base\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"That's the uncommon practice. And it starts with understanding that your reactivity is not your enemy. It's your attachment system's way of saying: this person matters. Don't lose them.\\\"}}]]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L16\\\",null,{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Why Your Partner Triggers You More Than Anyone Else on Earth\\\",\\\"slug\\\":\\\"why-your-partner-triggers-you-more-than-anyone\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"cl